ifferences between women in this class, and illustrate how the experience women had of property in this period was more complex than their legal and social status might suggest. This book will appeal to scholars in the fields of Irish history, gender and women’s studies.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aMarital propertyzIrelandxHistoryy18th century. 0aMarital propertyzIrelandxHistoryy19th century. 0aMarriagexEconomic aspectszIrelandxHistoryy18th century. 0aMarriagexEconomic aspectszIrelandxHistoryy19th century. 0aRight of propertyzIrelandxHistoryy18th century. 0aRight of propertyzIrelandxHistoryy19th century. 0aUpper class womenzIrelandxHistoryy18th century. 0aUpper class womenzIrelandxHistoryy19th century. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Ireland.2bisacsh  aIreland.  aIrish elite.  aIrish landed class.  aelite women.  afamily property distribution.  alanded families.  apower.  aproperty.  asettlements.  awills.1 aWilson, Deborah, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 1986 - 2013 eBook Packagez978311128363040uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978184779357740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781847793577423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781847793577/original  a978-3-11-128363-0  Manchester University Press 1986 - 2013 eBook Packagec1986d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles